TP4: Decision trees & random forests¶

The aim of this tutorial is to get familiar with the use of decision trees and their generalizations on simple examples using scikit-learn tools.

The data for this tutorial is famous. Called, the iris dataset, it contains four variables measuring various parts of iris flowers of three related species, and then a fourth variable with the species name. The reason it is so famous in machine learning and statistics communities is because the data requires very little preprocessing (i.e. no missing values, all features are floating numbers, etc.).

Step 2: create training and test sets¶

Create a new column that for each row, generates a random number between 0 and 1, and if that value is less than or equal to .75, then sets the value of that cell as True and false otherwise. This is a quick and dirty way of randomly assigning some rows to be used as the training data and some as the test data.

In [5]:

In each node we have 4 things : gini that represents the giny impurity of the node, the number of the samples in the node, the number of objects in each class and the predominant specie. The goal of each node is to separate the classes. The easiest one to separate, as mentioned above, is the setosa and the most important features are the ones associated with the petal. This is why the first node is able to separate the setosas from the others directly from the first node by checking petal width. If it's true, we go to the left and see the orange node with only setosas, the gini is 0 since we classified them and we have 37 samples. The same concept is used for the other nodes, when the gini is equal to 0 we have finished the classification in the node. Let us remind that this is a simple classifier, its performance depends highly on the training dataset and is not an accurate classifier in a lot of cases because of its reccurent overfitting issue. For these reasons, bagging and boosting were developed.

Feature selection using random forests byproducts¶

One of the interesting use cases for random forest is feature selection. One of the byproducts of trying lots of decision tree variations is that you can examine which variables are working best/worst in each tree.

When a certain tree uses one variable and another doesn't, you can compare the value lost or gained from the inclusion/exclusion of that variable. The good random forest implementations are going to do that for you, so all you need to do is know which method or variable to look at.

View feature importance¶

While we don't get regression coefficients like with ordinary least squares (OLS), we do get a score telling us how important each feature was in classifying. This is one of the most powerful parts of random forests, because we can clearly see that petal width was more important in classification than sepal width.

In [43]:
# View a list of the features and their importance scores
list(zip(train[features], rf.feature_importances_))
Out[43]:
[('sepal length (cm)', 0.08474010289429795),
 ('sepal width (cm)', 0.022461263894393204),
 ('petal length (cm)', 0.4464851467243143),
 ('petal width (cm)', 0.4463134864869946)]

This result is consistent with what was said before : petal features are more important than sepal features.

As expected, the trees do not use all the features but only a selection of them. Same goes for the training data. The out of bag data is the data not used for training the algorithm. We can use it later for the test. We find an accuracy of 94% which is close to a single decision tree, we will now try to optimize the 3 parameters (max_depth, min_samples_leaf, min_samples_split) to improve our score.

Max_depth

In [46]:
depths = np.arange(1,15)
score = []
for depth in depths:
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs = -1, random_state = 0, max_depth = depth)
    clf.fit(train[features], y)
    score.append(clf.score(test[features],y_test))
In [47]:
plt.ylabel('Score')
plt.xlabel('max_depth')
plt.grid()
plt.xlim(0,15)
plt.plot(depths, score)
Out[47]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1f2729e8f28>]

Here we notice that the max depth, when under 4, can have a small impact on our score. However, after a certain depth, it becomes unecessary to add more depth to the trees because it has no impact on our performance. We can also mention that we find a high score for a depth of 1 where we have 'stumps', and this random forests is really good at making bad classifiers (stumps) a good one by putting the results together. Now let's see what happens with the min_samples_leaf

In [48]:
leafs = np.arange(1,40)
score = []
for leaf in leafs:
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs = 2, random_state = 0, min_samples_leaf = leaf)
    clf.fit(train[features], y)
    score.append(clf.score(test[features],y_test))

We notice that this parameter does not impact our score a lot if we are under 19 | 20. However, after 20 we notice that our score only get lowers as min_samples_leaf gets bigger. Let's now change them together to see how it impacts our results.

In [52]:
depths = np.arange(1,10)
leafs = np.arange(1,10)
score = []
points = []
for depth in depths:
    for leaf in leafs:
        clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs = -1, random_state = 0, max_depth = depth, min_samples_leaf = leaf)
        clf.fit(train[features], y)
        score.append(clf.score(test[features],y_test))
        points.append([depth,leaf])

Step 5: a small example of regression using random forests¶

Random forest is capable of learning without carefully crafted data transformations. Take the the $f(x) = \sin(x)$ function for example.

Create some fake data and add a little noise.

In [65]:
x = np.random.uniform(-2.5, 2.5, 1000)
y = np.sin(x) + np.random.normal(0, .1, 1000)

plt.plot(x,y,'ko',markersize=1,label='data')
plt.plot(np.arange(-2.5,2.5,0.1),np.sin(np.arange(-2.5,2.5,0.1)),'r-',label='ref')
plt.legend(loc = 'best')
plt.show()

If we try and build a basic linear model to predict y using x we end up with a straight line that sort of bisects the sin(x) function. Whereas if we use a random forest, it does a much better job of approximating the sin(x) curve and we get something that looks much more like the true function.

Based on this example, we will illustrate how the random forest isn't bound by linear constraints.

You may use half of points for training and others to test predictions. Then you will have an idea of how far the random forest predictor fits the sinus curve.

To this aim, you will need to use the model RandomForestRegressor. Be careful that when only 1 feature x is used as an input, you will need to reshape it by x.reshape(-1,1) when using methods fit and predict.

Indication¶

One clever way to compare models when using scikit-learnis to make a loop on models as follows:

In [109]:
models = [RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=30, max_depth=4),
          RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=30, max_depth=1),
          RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=1, max_depth=4),
          LinearRegression()]

x_axis = np.linspace(-2.5,-2.5,1000)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=4, figsize=(15, 8), sharey = True)

for i, model in enumerate(models):
    print(i,str(model))
    model.fit(x[0::2].reshape(-1, 1),y[0::2])
    result = model.predict(x[:,None])
    axes[i].plot(x,y,'ko',markersize=1,label='data')
    axes[i].plot(np.arange(-2.5,2.5,0.1),np.sin(np.arange(-2.5,2.5,0.1)),'r-',label='ref')
    axes[i].scatter(x,result, label = str(model))
    axes[i].set_title(str(model)[:21])
#     axes[i].legend(loc = 'best')
plt.legend()

0 RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=4, n_estimators=30)
1 RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=1, n_estimators=30)
2 RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=4, n_estimators=1)
3 LinearRegression()
Out[109]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x1f27153cc50>

Here we can see that linear regression predicts a line for our sin function, with a random forest regression (n_estimators 30 and 4 in max_depth) we estimate far better our sin function. When we use only 1 as max_depth we find a function that is similar to the relu activation function. When we use n_estimators as 1 as 4 in max_depth we fit the curve well but not as good as having the two parameters optimized (30,4)

To sum up :

  • Decision Trees is a weak classifier because its performance depends highly on the training data and the model is prone to overfitting.
  • Random forests puts together weak classifiers together and makes one strong classifier by combining the results (mean for regression or vote for classification)
  • Each tree in the forest can learn from the previous tree mistakes. This is why a weight can be attributed to each tree depending on its performance to make the final decision.
  • Random forests is an accurate regressor/classifier, however it is less explainable than one decision tree or logistic regression. It also takes more time than these models.
  • Gradient boosting is a way to make this model more accurate.

Pruning trees: not available in scikit-learn.¶

Since post-pruning of tree is not implemented in scikit-learn, you may think of coding your own pruning function. For instance, taking into account the numer of samples per leaf as proposed below:

In [110]:
# Pruning function (useful ?)
def prune(decisiontree, min_samples_leaf = 1):
    if decisiontree.min_samples_leaf >= min_samples_leaf:
        raise Exception('Tree already more pruned')
    else:
        decisiontree.min_samples_leaf = min_samples_leaf
        tree = decisiontree.tree_
        for i in range(tree.node_count):
            n_samples = tree.n_node_samples[i]
            if n_samples <= min_samples_leaf:
                tree.children_left[i]=-1
                tree.children_right[i]=-1
